01:01:06,376 --> 01:01:09,545
pack some clothes
and his precious saxophone.

731
01:01:11,214 --> 01:01:13,174
How long is he staying for?

732
01:01:13,258 --> 01:01:16,678
Search me.
I guess we're abandoned.

733
01:01:43,039 --> 01:01:45,416
Goddamn it!

734
01:01:46,793 --> 01:01:48,711
Are you okay?

735
01:01:59,264 --> 01:02:02,600
There was a letter from Dickie
in with my perfume.

736
01:02:04,686 --> 01:02:08,357
You realize it's more
than just a few days.

737
01:02:08,439 --> 01:02:12,443
He's thinking of moving to Rome.

738
01:02:12,485 --> 01:02:14,905
The thing is,

739
01:02:14,988 --> 01:02:17,657
the night before
he left, we...

740
01:02:17,740 --> 01:02:19,827
we talked about
moving together...

741
01:02:21,536 --> 01:02:23,621
somewhere north,
and I suppose I...

742
01:02:26,250 --> 01:02:29,502
put some pressure on him
about getting married.

743
01:02:31,505 --> 01:02:33,673
I just...

744
01:02:35,677 --> 01:02:37,970
I just might have scared him off.

745
01:02:43,642 --> 01:02:46,312
There's a side to him...

746
01:02:46,354 --> 01:02:49,690
when our heads
are on the pillow...

747
01:02:49,773 --> 01:02:53,152
I know no one else sees
that's so tender.

748
01:02:55,196 --> 01:02:58,492
I think I should come with you
to Rome and confront him.

749
01:03:04,831 --> 01:03:07,710
He hates
being confronted.

750
01:03:09,503 --> 01:03:11,713
I think you're right.

751
01:03:20,681 --> 01:03:22,807
Grazie.
Checking in.

752
01:03:31,233 --> 01:03:33,193
Checking in.

753
01:03:33,234 --> 01:03:37,365
- Signor Ripley?
- It's me.

754
01:03:39,534 --> 01:03:42,661
Signor Greenleaf.

755
01:03:42,703 --> 01:03:45,206
Of course.
Welcome back.

756
01:03:45,290 --> 01:03:47,667
Thank you.

757
01:04:05,142 --> 01:04:07,061
Pronto?

758
01:04:07,145 --> 01:04:10,523
Yes, I'd like to telephone
the Hotel Goldoni.

759
01:04:10,565 --> 01:04:15,195
- Si, signor.
- I want to speak to Thomas Ripley.

760
01:04:15,237 --> 01:04:18,199
- Ripley? Subito.
- Yes. Grazie.

761
01:04:26,164 --> 01:04:31,170
Pronto.

762
01:04:31,253 --> 01:04:33,172
Signor Greenleaf,
Signor Ripley's not there.

763
01:04:33,256 --> 01:04:35,382
- He's not there?
- No, signor.

764
01:04:35,424 --> 01:04:38,177
Well, I would like
to leave a message.

765
01:04:38,260 --> 01:04:40,513
- He's not there? I'll leave a message.
- No, signor.

766
01:04:40,596 --> 01:04:42,723
- Got your call.
- Got your call.

767
01:04:42,765 --> 01:04:44,726
- Dinner tonight...
- Dinner tonight...

768
01:04:44,768 --> 01:04:46,727
- sounds fine.
- sounds fine.

769
01:04:46,769 --> 01:04:50,274
- Ripley. Ripley.
- Ripley.

770
01:04:50,357 --> 01:04:53,860
- Dickie Greenleaf.
- Dickie Greenleaf.

771
01:04:53,943 --> 01:04:56,905
- Yes. Greenleaf.
- Greenleaf.

772
01:04:56,989 --> 01:04:59,115
At the Grand.

773
01:04:59,199 --> 01:05:02,619
And I'd like to have
this wallet embossed.

774
01:05:02,702 --> 01:05:04,620
I don't know
the word in Italian.

775
01:05:04,704 --> 01:05:06,706
Embossed. Of course,
Signor Greenleaf.

776
01:05:06,790 --> 01:05:08,791
Thank you.

777
01:05:12,504 --> 01:05:16,217
Dickie!
It's...

778
01:05:19,303 --> 01:05:21,222
- Oh, my gosh.
- Meredith.

779
01:05:21,305 --> 01:05:23,224
- Ciao!
- Ciao. Come in. Come in.

780
01:05:23,307 --> 01:05:25,934
But you're going skiing
with those Yankees, aren't you?

781
01:05:26,018 --> 01:05:30,689
- What?
- At Christmas. To Cortina.

782
01:05:30,773 --> 01:05:32,734
- With Freddie Miles.
- How did you know that?

783
01:05:32,817 --> 01:05:36,820
Oh! Everybody
knows Freddie Miles.

784
01:05:39,532 --> 01:05:41,534
Is Freddie in Rome?

785
01:05:41,617 --> 01:05:43,536
- Now?
- Yeah.

786
01:05:43,620 --> 01:05:45,955
Oh, I don't think so.

787
01:05:46,038 --> 01:05:50,460
But I... But I've met him,
Of course, and we've chatted.

788
01:05:50,501 --> 01:05:54,131
And I know about you...

789
01:05:54,215 --> 01:05:56,799
and Marge in Mongi.

790
01:05:56,883 --> 01:06:00,095
What an unreliable
rat you are.

791
01:06:00,179 --> 01:06:02,430
Well, Freddie said
you were a rat.

792
01:06:02,514 --> 01:06:04,809
And I thought
to myself,

793
01:06:04,850 --> 01:06:07,978
"Ah, now I know why
he travels under 'R.'"

794
01:06:08,061 --> 01:06:10,397
I've left Marge,
Meredith.

795
01:06:10,480 --> 01:06:12,691
And Mongi.

796
01:06:12,774 --> 01:06:16,028
- So the rat's here in Rome.
- Oh, I'm sorry.

797
01:06:16,112 --> 01:06:19,240
Oh, don't be sorry, no.
I've never been happier.

798
01:06:19,323 --> 01:06:22,618
I... I feel like
I've been handed a new life.

799
01:06:22,701 --> 01:06:26,580
The truth is that if you've had money
your entire life,

800
01:06:26,664 --> 01:06:29,959
either you despise it,
which we do... agreed?

801
01:06:30,042 --> 01:06:33,004
You're only truly comfortable
around other people...

802
01:06:33,046 --> 01:06:36,131
who have it
and despise it.

803
01:06:36,215 --> 01:06:38,134
I know.

804
01:06:39,636 --> 01:06:42,263
I've never admitted that
to anyone.

805
01:06:47,811 --> 01:06:51,064
Because my friend
Mr. Greenleaf, Signor Greenleaf and I,

806
01:06:51,148 --> 01:06:53,067
are on a little spending spree.

807
01:06:53,150 --> 01:06:57,112
- I see.
- We're behaving very badly.

808
01:06:57,195 --> 01:07:01,658
Oh, I love Italian money. So dark.
Doesn't make you feel guilty.

809
01:07:01,742 --> 01:07:03,661
- Gr-r-razie.
- Thank you.

810
01:07:14,255 --> 01:07:17,758
I don't want too many large bills.
No one will change them.

811
01:07:17,842 --> 01:07:19,928
Tutto bene,
Signor Greenleaf.

812
01:07:35,777 --> 01:07:39,405
- I really like this too.
- I think I'm having that too.

813
01:07:45,787 --> 01:07:48,248
Tomorrow.

814
01:07:53,086 --> 01:07:55,547
- Arrivederci.
- Arrivederci. Oops!

815
01:07:56,799 --> 01:07:58,717
- Ciao.
- Ciao.

816
01:08:04,223 --> 01:08:08,645
I know you're a jazz fiend,
but do you absolutely hate the opera?

817
01:08:11,855 --> 01:08:14,776
I've...
I've...

818
01:08:14,817 --> 01:08:18,446
been trying to give
my tickets away.

819
01:08:18,529 --> 01:08:22,991
It's tomorrow. But if
you were prepared to be dragged...

820
01:08:24,494 --> 01:08:26,663
You could drag me.

821
01:10:14,940 --> 01:10:18,653
Feodor Chaliapin.
It's the whole Russian baritone.

822
01:10:18,737 --> 01:10:22,115
Thank you so much
for inviting me tonight.

823
01:10:22,199 --> 01:10:26,035
Can you bear it?
We hear you are a friend of Freddie's.

824
01:10:26,118 --> 01:10:29,289
He has "I hate opera"
tattooed on his chest.

825
01:10:29,372 --> 01:10:31,875
There's room for a whole
libretto on Freddie's chest.

826
01:10:33,961 --> 01:10:36,296
I'm sure
we've met before.

827
01:10:36,379 --> 01:10:39,300
I was sure we'd met before.
Weren't you, Ted?

828
01:10:39,383 --> 01:10:41,427
Dick is Herbert
Greenleaf's boy.

829
01:10:41,468 --> 01:10:44,054
- I know.
- Yes, I think we have.

830
01:10:44,137 --> 01:10:48,225
One minute you people are children,
and the next you're getting tattooed.

831
01:10:50,186 --> 01:10:52,771
- Cheers.
- Cheers.

832
01:10:54,857 --> 01:10:56,817
Cheers.

833
01:11:01,114 --> 01:11:03,532
- Excuse me.
- Prego.

834
01:11:03,616 --> 01:11:05,952
Oh!
Excuse me.

835
01:11:06,036 --> 01:11:08,287
- Hello.
- Hello.

836
01:11:09,789 --> 01:11:11,707
- Tom!
- Marge!

837
01:11:11,791 --> 01:11:14,919
How are you?
What are you doing in Rome?

838
01:11:15,002 --> 01:11:18,631
- Is he here? Are you with Dickie?
- No. Um, no.

839
01:11:18,714 --> 01:11:21,802
Um, hello.
Um, I'm Tom Ripley.

840
01:11:21,843 --> 01:11:24,262
Peter Smith-Kingsley. I've heard
all about you from Marge and Dickie.

841
01:11:24,346 --> 01:11:27,308
- Ditto.
- No... No glasses.

842
01:11:27,350 --> 01:11:30,184
So, where are you hiding him?
He's impossible, isn't he?

843
01:11:30,268 --> 01:11:32,396
Is he really not here?

844
01:11:32,479 --> 01:11:36,149
Marge, you know Dickie has
"I hate opera" tattooed on his chest.

845
01:11:36,191 --> 01:11:39,236
- I thought you were going to Venice.
- Yes, what happened with that?

846
01:11:39,319 --> 01:11:41,237
I heard you were
desperate to come.

847
01:11:41,321 --> 01:11:43,324
I was rather looking forward
to rowing you around.

848
01:11:43,365 --> 01:11:47,077
I am. I really am.

849
01:11:47,161 --> 01:11:50,372
I've been traveling, and I just can't
seem to get that far north.

850
01:11:50,455 --> 01:11:52,333
Well, you should hurry,
before we sink.

851
01:11:52,375 --> 01:11:55,503
Look, let me give you
the telephone number.

852
01:11:55,544 --> 01:11:58,423
There. Oh, look.
There's Meredith.

853
01:11:58,506 --> 01:12:01,759
Meredith. What's her name,
Marge? The textile people.

854
01:12:01,842 --> 01:12:05,305
Um, come on. Some of us
spent Christmas at her house.

855
01:12:05,388 --> 01:12:09,142
I don't know her.

856
01:12:09,226 --> 01:12:13,020
He hasn't called.
He's hardly written.

857
01:12:13,062 --> 01:12:15,191
Just these cryptic
notes, you know?

858
01:12:15,274 --> 01:12:17,317
You don't just dump people.

859
01:12:17,401 --> 01:12:21,029
Look, will we see you later,
Or are you with people?

860
01:12:21,071 --> 01:12:24,074
- Uh, I can't later.
- Well, how about tomorrow?

861
01:12:24,157 --> 01:12:26,076
Yes, uh,
maybe in the morning?

862
01:12:26,160 --> 01:12:29,829
Do you know Cafe Dinelli
at the Piazza di Spagna?

863
01:12:29,913 --> 01:12:33,376
- I know the Piazza. What time?
- 10:30?

864
01:12:33,459 --> 01:12:35,712
- We'll be there.
- Okay.

865
01:12:35,754 --> 01:12:37,797
So I'll see you
in the morning, Marge?

866
01:12:37,880 --> 01:12:40,925
10:30?
Very nice to meet you.

867
01:12:41,008 --> 01:12:43,052
And you.

868
01:12:45,929 --> 01:12:47,807
Come on.

869
01:12:47,890 --> 01:12:51,811
Come on.
Let's go back in.

870
01:12:57,734 --> 01:13:00,820
I don't understand why
Tom's still in Rome.

871
01:13:00,904 --> 01:13:05,158
- Let's go.
- I thought you were enjoying yourself.

872
01:13:05,242 --> 01:13:07,535
Let's take a carrozza
and look at the moon.

873
01:13:07,619 --> 01:13:09,538
Are you crazy?
It's freezing out there.

874
01:13:09,621 --> 01:13:12,415
Come on. I need to talk to you.
Just the two of us.

875
01:13:12,498 --> 01:13:14,585
Okay.

876
01:13:18,380 --> 01:13:20,883
Don't worry, please.

877
01:13:20,966 --> 01:13:23,802
Don't worry.

878
01:13:23,886 --> 01:13:27,973
You're such a pal
to understand. I...

879
01:13:28,057 --> 01:13:30,184
It's like Marge is here
right now. I look at you,

880
01:13:30,268 --> 01:13:32,353
and I see her face.

881
01:13:32,436 --> 01:13:35,189
And I can't... No matter
what I'm feeling towards you...

882
01:13:35,272 --> 01:13:40,653
No. I absolutely...
understand. Ofc...

883
01:13:40,695 --> 01:13:44,198
Otherwise, you'd be
fighting me off.

884
01:13:44,281 --> 01:13:46,243
Beating you away.

885
01:14:24,907 --> 01:14:28,160
But will you meet me
tomorrow?

886
01:14:28,202 --> 01:14:31,455
Just to say good-bye properly,
you know, in the daylight,

887
01:14:31,539 --> 01:14:33,666
so it's not just this.

888
01:14:33,750 --> 01:14:36,502
Of course. Meredith, I'm sorry.
Of course I'll meet you.

889
01:14:36,586 --> 01:14:41,841
You should always
save pain for daylight.

890
01:14:41,882 --> 01:14:45,178
Why don't we have coffee
in the morning at Dinelli's?

891
01:14:45,262 --> 01:14:47,430
Uh, by the Spanish Steps.

892
01:14:47,514 --> 01:14:49,348
Exactly. 10:30?

893
01:14:52,060 --> 01:14:54,687
- 10:15.
- Okay.

894
01:14:54,729 --> 01:14:56,899
Okay.

895
01:15:48,117 --> 01:15:50,453
- Grazie.
- Peter?

896
01:15:50,537 --> 01:15:54,041
Hello.
It's Meredith Logue.

897
01:15:54,125 --> 01:15:56,793
Of course it is.
Meredith, hello. Sorry.

898
01:15:56,876 --> 01:15:59,922
- I was half asleep. How are you?
- How are you?

899
01:16:00,005 --> 01:16:02,382
This is Marge Sherwood.
Meredith Logue.

900
01:16:02,424 --> 01:16:05,470
How do you do?

901
01:16:05,553 --> 01:16:08,889
Do join us, won't you?
We're just waiting for a friend.

902
01:16:08,930 --> 01:16:11,684
I... I won't, actually.
I think there's...

903
01:16:11,767 --> 01:16:14,353
- Did we see you at the opera last night?
- Uh...

904
01:16:14,436 --> 01:16:17,147
Are you waiting for Dickie?

905
01:16:17,231 --> 01:16:21,361
Dickie? Do you... Do you...
Do you know Dickie?

906
01:16:21,444 --> 01:16:24,571
You were at the opera.
Oh, that explains... Yes, I was there.

907
01:16:24,655 --> 01:16:28,201
I was there with Dickie.

908
01:16:29,285 --> 01:16:32,038
I knew it.

909
01:16:32,122 --> 01:16:34,332
I told you.

910
01:16:36,417 --> 01:16:40,922
Marge, I don't know you,
so I've got no right to...

911
01:16:41,005 --> 01:16:44,218
Dickie loves you.
He's... Well...

912
01:16:44,301 --> 01:16:47,428
I think you'll find
he's on his way home to you.

913
01:16:47,511 --> 01:16:51,557
Well, how-how-how
would you know that?

914
01:16:52,809 --> 01:16:55,354
He... told me everything.

915
01:16:55,437 --> 01:17:00,359
No, I was supposed to meet him
15 minutes ago, so, uh,

916
01:17:00,443 --> 01:17:02,860
I'm gonna go now,
I think.

917
01:17:05,155 --> 01:17:07,241
God, unless he meant us
to meet.

918
01:17:07,325 --> 01:17:09,494
That'd be a little cruel,
wouldn't it?

919
01:17:09,577 --> 01:17:11,995
No, no, we're
meeting another friend.

920
01:17:12,037 --> 01:17:14,874
- Tom Ripley.
- Do you know Tom Ripley?

921
01:17:14,957 --> 01:17:19,796
No, no. I've heard about him,
of course, but I didn't meet him, no.

922
01:17:19,838 --> 01:17:22,340
Not for me. No, grazie.

923
01:17:27,679 --> 01:17:30,598
Hope I didn't
complicate matters.

924
01:17:30,682 --> 01:17:36,021
God, nothing, nothing...
untoward happened.

925
01:17:36,063 --> 01:17:40,316
No, there is nothing to prevent you
from welcoming him back,

926
01:17:40,358 --> 01:17:42,319
from marrying him.

927
01:17:46,865 --> 01:17:49,576
Good-bye.
I'm happy to put a face to a name.

928
01:17:49,659 --> 01:17:52,163
Good-bye, Peter.
Please, don't get up.

929
01:18:12,683 --> 01:18:15,811
Now I don't know what to think.
Do you think he's coming back?

930
01:18:17,396 --> 01:18:20,816
Sorry. Sorry.
Had to renew my papers.

931
01:18:20,900 --> 01:18:23,235
Never one stamp when they
can make you line up for three.

932
01:18:23,277 --> 01:18:25,405
- Have you been waiting long?
- Not at all.

933
01:18:25,488 --> 01:18:28,199
- Morning, Tom.
- Hi. Sorry.

934
01:18:28,282 --> 01:18:30,243
You okay? You look like
you've seen a ghost.

935
01:18:30,285 --> 01:18:32,996
Dickie was at the opera
last night.

936
01:18:33,079 --> 01:18:36,416
I don't believe that. Uh...
Wild horses couldn't drag Dickie...

937
01:18:36,458 --> 01:18:38,751
Well, he was there
with someone, you know,

938
01:18:38,835 --> 01:18:41,338
so I suppose she must
have dragged him.

939
01:18:41,421 --> 01:18:44,257
It's not fair.

940
01:18:44,299 --> 01:18:48,470
I think I'm going back to Mongi.
I think Dickie's coming home.

941
01:18:48,553 --> 01:18:51,182
Really? I... Well,
that's just swell.

942
01:18:51,265 --> 01:18:53,893
No, you know, you're
way ahead of me. Great.

943
01:18:53,976 --> 01:18:55,936
That was rather moving
when I heard... I'm sorry.

944
01:18:56,019 --> 01:18:58,439
Meredith is the American girl
I saw at the opera last night.

945
01:18:58,481 --> 01:19:02,568
- She's been seeing something of Dickie.
- Oh, my God.

946
01:19:02,652 --> 01:19:06,113
But the point is,
Dickie... and we all know this.

947
01:19:06,196 --> 01:19:09,867
Dickie loves Marge.
And he misses her.

948
01:19:09,951 --> 01:19:12,704
I feel guilty.
Marge doesn't understand this,

949
01:19:12,788 --> 01:19:15,623
but whenever Dickie does
something, I feel guilty.

950
01:19:15,706 --> 01:19:18,001
As if that makes sense.

951
01:20:41,420 --> 01:20:43,380
Dickie.

952
01:20:45,049 --> 01:20:47,426
Dickie, come on. It's me.

953
01:20:49,887 --> 01:20:51,805
It's Freddie.
Let me in.

954
01:20:54,851 --> 01:20:56,769
Dickie.

955
01:21:02,067 --> 01:21:04,860
Hello, Freddie.
It's Tom.

956
01:21:05,946 --> 01:21:08,907
Um, where's Dickie?

957
01:21:08,948 --> 01:21:10,909
How are you?

958
01:21:10,951 --> 01:21:14,036
I'm good. Uh, yes, thank you.
He's gone. He went to dinner.

959
01:21:14,078 --> 01:21:18,458
- He's at Otello's. You know Otello's?
- No, no, no.

960
01:21:18,541 --> 01:21:21,336
I... I don't think
he's at dinner at 6:30 PM.

961
01:21:21,420 --> 01:21:24,715
If you said he was still at lunch,
maybe I'd believe you.

962
01:21:24,756 --> 01:21:28,385
You know?
Incredible.

963
01:21:28,427 --> 01:21:32,389
I mean, the guy just, you know,
disappeared off the face of the earth.

964
01:21:34,558 --> 01:21:36,477
I guess.

965
01:21:37,603 --> 01:21:40,689
The landlady,
as far as I could tell...

966
01:21:40,773 --> 01:21:44,568
The landlady said
he was here right now.

967
01:21:44,610 --> 01:21:46,862
Search the place.

968
01:21:46,945 --> 01:21:50,324
I... I just don't... I don't know why you'd
imagine that Dickie would hide from you.

969
01:21:50,407 --> 01:21:52,326
Because he's been
hiding from me.

970
01:21:54,496 --> 01:21:58,332
- What happened at Christmas?
- What about Christmas?

971
01:21:58,416 --> 01:22:01,545
He was supposed to come skiing.
I didn't get a cable...

972
01:22:01,628 --> 01:22:03,838
or a call or a little note or a...

973
01:22:03,923 --> 01:22:08,426
Frankly, a fart.

974
01:22:08,509 --> 01:22:10,763
Well, he's been very involved
with his music.

975
01:22:10,845 --> 01:22:15,059
Um, I think his theory... is...

976
01:22:15,142 --> 01:22:19,730
that you have to go into a cocoon,
uh, before you can be a butterfly.

977
01:22:19,813 --> 01:22:22,357
Which is horseshit.

978
01:22:22,440 --> 01:22:25,903
You hear him play this thing?
Well, he can't.

979
01:22:28,781 --> 01:22:30,867
How did you find him?

980
01:22:30,950 --> 01:22:33,952
It's such an out-of-the-way apartment.
Can I fix you a drink?

981
01:22:33,994 --> 01:22:36,998
No, thanks.
At the American Express.

982
01:22:40,418 --> 01:22:42,837
Some kid.

983
01:22:48,343 --> 01:22:51,304
Are you living here?

984
01:22:51,345 --> 01:22:54,473
No, no. I'm staying here
for a few days.

985
01:22:57,143 --> 01:22:59,813
But...

986
01:22:59,854 --> 01:23:03,566
It's a new piano.
Probably shouldn't...

987
01:23:08,112 --> 01:23:10,699
Probably shouldn't...

988
01:23:13,661 --> 01:23:17,414
Did this place come furnished?

989
01:23:17,497 --> 01:23:20,668
It doesn't
Look like Dickie's, uh...

990
01:23:20,751 --> 01:23:23,836
It's really horrible,
isn't it?

991
01:23:25,423 --> 01:23:28,925
It's so, uh, bourgeois.

992
01:23:38,435 --> 01:23:40,647
Oh, that's a, uh...
You should... Watch that.

993
01:23:40,730 --> 01:23:43,858
Excuse...
Excuse me.

994
01:23:43,900 --> 01:23:45,861
Excuse me.

995
01:23:48,864 --> 01:23:53,534
In fact, the only thing that looks
like Dickie... is you.

996
01:23:53,576 --> 01:23:55,620
- Hardly.
- Hmm.

997
01:23:57,581 --> 01:24:00,291
Have you done something
to your hair?

998
01:24:00,374 --> 01:24:02,378
Is there something
you'd like to say, Freddie?

999
01:24:02,461 --> 01:24:04,879
- What?
- You have something you'd like to say?

1000
01:24:04,921 --> 01:24:07,299
I think I'm saying it.

1001
01:24:08,759 --> 01:24:11,886
Something's going on.

1002
01:24:11,969 --> 01:24:14,806
Either he's converted
to Christianity,

1003
01:24:16,016 --> 01:24:17,934
or there's something else.

1004
01:24:19,395 --> 01:24:21,521
Well, I would suggest you
ask Dickie that yourself.

1005
01:24:21,605 --> 01:24:24,484
Otello's is on della Croce
just off the Corso.

1006
01:24:24,567 --> 01:24:28,028
Is it on della Croce
just off the Corso?

1007
01:24:30,114 --> 01:24:34,369
Sure. You're a
quick study, aren't you?

1008
01:24:34,453 --> 01:24:36,371
Last time you didn't know
you ass from your elbow.

1009
01:24:36,454 --> 01:24:38,873
Now you're giving me directions.

1010
01:24:38,956 --> 01:24:42,710
That's not fair. You probably
do know your ass from your elbow.

1011
01:24:45,631 --> 01:24:47,549
I'll see you.

1012
01:24:59,685 --> 01:25:02,272
No Dickie Greenleaf. Thomas Ripley.

1013
01:25:02,355 --> 01:25:05,775
Si.

1014
01:25:10,990 --> 01:25:12,950
Ciao, Dickie.

1015
01:25:17,455 --> 01:25:19,916
Dickie doesn't
play the piano.

1016
01:25:21,458 --> 01:25:23,377
Tommy.

1017
01:25:23,461 --> 01:25:25,379
Tommy!

1018
01:25:25,462 --> 01:25:27,381
Tommy!

1019
01:26:05,921 --> 01:26:08,715
Oh!
You're making me laugh.

1020
01:26:08,799 --> 01:26:12,595
No. You're just so drunk.
Oh. You're just...

1021
01:26:12,678 --> 01:26:16,015
What can you do, eh?
You should see my other friends.

1022
01:26:16,057 --> 01:26:18,476
What can you do?

1023
01:26:18,559 --> 01:26:21,771
Yes.
Such a pig.

1024
01:26:25,274 --> 01:26:30,530
Hey, if I'm drunk,
think what her husband's saying.

1025
01:27:17,954 --> 01:27:20,332
- La polizia.
- Dickie Greenleaf?

1026
01:27:20,415 --> 01:27:23,417
- Yes.
- Inspector Roverini.

1027
01:27:23,500 --> 01:27:25,503
- Can we come in?
- Please.

1028
01:27:33,261 --> 01:27:35,555
It's a terrible shock,
huh?

1029
01:27:35,638 --> 01:27:39,350
W... What time did Signor Miles
leave yesterday?

1030
01:27:39,434 --> 01:27:43,439
Oh, um, I can't be
certain exactly. I...

1031
01:27:43,522 --> 01:27:45,440
8:00, 9:00.

1032
01:27:48,319 --> 01:27:52,740
We'd both taken on, uh,
far too many drinks.

1033
01:27:52,782 --> 01:27:57,369
But it was dark. It was certainly dark
when I... when I walked him to his car.

1034
01:27:57,453 --> 01:28:00,414
So he drove away,
and, uh, you did what?

1035
01:28:00,456 --> 01:28:03,543
I went to bed.

1036
01:28:03,626 --> 01:28:08,297
Freddie's a big man, but I'm in trouble
after a couple of drinks.

1037
01:28:08,380 --> 01:28:11,759
I've been suffering all...

1038
01:28:11,800 --> 01:28:13,886
Who found him?

1039
01:28:13,970 --> 01:28:16,556
You understand, I must ask you...

1040
01:28:16,639 --> 01:28:19,183
to stay in Rome,
Signor Greenleaf.

1041
01:28:19,267 --> 01:28:22,604
Yes, if it's gonna help,
certainly.

1042
01:28:22,646 --> 01:28:26,441
So, the doctor, he has to make
the, um...

1043
01:28:29,944 --> 01:28:33,156
- Postmortem.
- Yeah, exactly.

1044
01:28:33,240 --> 01:28:35,910
But, you know,
his first conclusion...

1045
01:28:35,993 --> 01:28:41,039
was that Signor Miles was killed
not later than 7:00 yesterday evening.

1046
01:28:41,123 --> 01:28:44,501
Well, he certainly wasn't dead
when he drove away in his car.

1047
01:28:46,629 --> 01:28:48,547
No.

1048
01:29:13,865 --> 01:29:16,367
It's okay.

1049
01:29:16,451 --> 01:29:18,829
- Okay?
- Si, si.

1050
01:29:29,214 --> 01:29:32,843
- Did he kill Freddie?
- Marge. When did you get here?

1051
01:29:32,884 --> 01:29:35,513
Tell me the truth.
Did he kill Freddie?

1052
01:29:35,596 --> 01:29:39,140
I'd swear he didn't.
Of course he didn't.

1053
01:29:39,224 --> 01:29:43,437
I tried again.
Waiting here, watching for him.

1054
01:29:43,520 --> 01:29:47,107
Instead, it's you.
Whenever I look for Dickie, I find you.

1055
01:29:49,026 --> 01:29:51,987
What happened to your face?

1056
01:29:52,071 --> 01:29:54,031
Dickie...
Dickie did it.

1057
01:29:54,072 --> 01:29:56,325
- Dickie?
- My face. There was an argument.

1058
01:29:56,409 --> 01:29:59,078
I... I said some things
I shouldn't have said and I...

1059
01:29:59,161 --> 01:30:02,791
About you. About the appalling way
he's treating you, all of us.

1060
01:30:02,874 --> 01:30:05,168
And the next thing I know,
he's launched himself at me.

1061
01:30:05,251 --> 01:30:07,379
- Are you getting on?
- What?

1062
01:30:07,421 --> 01:30:09,589
Get on.
I'll take you to him.

1063
01:30:54,093 --> 01:30:56,304
- Where does he live?
- We passed it a few blocks back.

1064
01:30:56,387 --> 01:30:58,806
It's where the police were.
The Palazzo Gioia.

1065
01:31:00,809 --> 01:31:03,811
Look, they don't even know I'm in Rome,
and I'm not gonna incriminate Dickie.

1066
01:31:03,853 --> 01:31:05,897
Well, perhaps
I shouldn't go either.

1067
01:31:05,981 --> 01:31:09,608
No. Well, go if you want to, but just
don't talk to the police about my face.

1068
01:31:09,650 --> 01:31:13,030
If they know he hit me and his temper,
then he could've hit Freddie.

1069
01:31:13,113 --> 01:31:15,073
I'll catch up
with you later.

1070
01:31:33,301 --> 01:31:36,262
Signor Greenleaf!

1071
01:31:36,345 --> 01:31:38,931
It's Signor Greenleaf!
Presto, presto!

1072
01:31:44,395 --> 01:31:46,605
Open the door!

1073
01:31:46,689 --> 01:31:49,067
Open up!

1074
01:31:49,150 --> 01:31:51,402
I live here!

1075
01:31:52,569 --> 01:31:54,531
Mr. Greenleaf!

1076
01:31:55,865 --> 01:31:58,075
Can we go up?
Do you mind?

1077
01:31:58,159 --> 01:32:00,745
Of course.
What happened to your face?

1078
01:32:00,829 --> 01:32:04,499
My scooter. I fell off
getting chased by photographers.

1079
01:32:04,583 --> 01:32:08,627
The telephone, the press,
I've been... I'm feeling hounded.

1080
01:32:08,711 --> 01:32:10,839
Do you think you could
not give out my address?

1081
01:32:10,880 --> 01:32:15,510
Never. We've had many requests,
and we say no, even to your fiancée.

1082
01:32:15,594 --> 01:32:17,555
I really don't want
to see anybody.

1083
01:32:17,596 --> 01:32:20,390
- Even your fiancée?
- Even her.

1084
01:32:23,477 --> 01:32:26,689
- What about Thomas Ripley?
- What about Tom Ripley?

1085
01:32:28,691 --> 01:32:30,692
You and Signor Ripley went to San Remo.
Is that right?

1086
01:32:30,734 --> 01:32:33,862
Yes, we... We went to San Remo.
That was months ago.

1087
01:32:33,946 --> 01:32:36,114
November, I thought.
Was it?

1088
01:32:36,198 --> 01:32:39,744
- Did you speak to Tom?
- November 7 is my information.

1089
01:32:39,827 --> 01:32:42,581
I don't remember
the exact date.

1090
01:32:42,622 --> 01:32:47,084
- When did you last see Signor Ripley?
- A few days ago.

1091
01:32:47,126 --> 01:32:50,713
- Does he stay with you here?
- No.

1092
01:32:50,797 --> 01:32:53,175
No.

1093
01:32:54,550 --> 01:32:57,512
Here is a pattern.
Two days ago,

1094
01:32:57,595 --> 01:33:00,557
Freddie Miles is dead, hmm?

1095
01:33:01,808 --> 01:33:04,269
He leaves your apartment,

1096
01:33:05,354 --> 01:33:08,105
and he's murdered.

1097
01:33:08,189 --> 01:33:13,319
Yesterday, a little boat
is found in San Remo full of rocks.

1098
01:33:13,403 --> 01:33:18,283
And the owner tells the police
it was stolen on November7.

1099
01:33:18,325 --> 01:33:20,828
We look at hotel records...

1100
01:33:20,912 --> 01:33:23,706
and we see...

1101
01:33:23,789 --> 01:33:26,959
Dickie Greenleaf
is staying in San Remo.

1102
01:33:27,042 --> 01:33:30,796
And then our boatman remembers
two Americans taking a boat.

1103
01:33:30,880 --> 01:33:33,674
That is not a pattern.
That's a coincidence.

1104
01:33:33,757 --> 01:33:35,718
There must be 50 hotels
in San Remo.

1105
01:33:35,802 --> 01:33:38,638
There were probably a hundred people
renting a boat that day.

1106
01:33:38,679 --> 01:33:41,183
Thirty-one people.

1107
01:33:41,266 --> 01:33:43,268
Thirty-one people.

1108
01:33:44,393 --> 01:33:46,312
Thirty-one, yeah.

1109
01:33:48,565 --> 01:33:51,151
- Marge Sherwood.
- That is Miss Sherwood now.

1110
01:33:59,910 --> 01:34:01,953
Let her in.

1111
01:34:01,995 --> 01:34:04,665
Let her in.
What's the difference? Let her in.

1112
01:34:07,125 --> 01:34:10,546
No! Actually...
Actually, no.

1113
01:34:10,629 --> 01:34:13,508
I would... I would
really appreciate it...

1114
01:34:13,591 --> 01:34:16,468
if you would ask Miss Sherwood
to come back later.

1115
01:34:21,014 --> 01:34:23,850
Thank you.

1116
01:34:23,935 --> 01:34:27,522
May I ask you...

1117
01:34:27,605 --> 01:34:31,150
Why would you speak to your friend
and not your fiancée?

1118
01:34:31,234 --> 01:34:34,569
Well, I...
I think I just said.

1119
01:34:34,654 --> 01:34:37,990
Um, Mr. Ripley was
handling some business for me.

1120
01:34:38,032 --> 01:34:40,660
Nor does Mr. Ripley
want to marry me...

1121
01:34:40,744 --> 01:34:44,789
and ask me every single day
if I'll marry him and when.

1122
01:34:45,957 --> 01:34:47,959
Do you keep a photograph
Of Signor Ripley?

1123
01:34:48,043 --> 01:34:51,880
I'm not in the habit of carrying
around photographs of my male friends.

1124
01:34:53,548 --> 01:34:55,466
Now I think I've upset you.

1125
01:34:55,550 --> 01:34:58,679
Sorry. My English,
perhaps, is coarse.

1126
01:34:58,720 --> 01:35:01,223
It is a little coarse,
yes.

1127
01:35:04,726 --> 01:35:06,644
I'm sorry.

1128
01:35:06,728 --> 01:35:11,691
But you... No one has seen
Signor Ripley since San Remo.

1129
01:35:11,775 --> 01:35:13,736
- I have.
- You have, yes.

1130
01:35:13,777 --> 01:35:16,530
And so has Miss Sherwood.
Ask her. And, um,

1131
01:35:16,572 --> 01:35:21,702
if I can remember the name
of the hotel he was staying at...

1132
01:35:21,786 --> 01:35:24,830
Um, the Goldoni.
Tom was staying at the Goldoni.

1133
01:35:24,914 --> 01:35:28,293
Goldoni. The Goldoni.
Good, good, but...

1134
01:35:28,376 --> 01:35:30,920
Yes, you are right.

1135
01:35:31,004 --> 01:35:33,256
You are right.
A coincidence.

1136
01:35:35,342 --> 01:35:38,929
I look forward
to our next meeting.

1137
01:35:39,012 --> 01:35:41,014
Hmm? When I will be more
careful with my English.

1138
01:35:41,097 --> 01:35:45,351
Ah. I have a witness
who thinks they saw two men...

1139
01:35:45,435 --> 01:35:47,354
getting into Mr. Miles' car.

1140
01:35:47,437 --> 01:35:51,316
And she wants to identify you
in a confronto.

1141
01:35:51,400 --> 01:35:53,902
Lineup. Tomorrow, then?

1142
01:35:55,404 --> 01:35:57,322
Uh, tomorrow.

1143
01:36:04,955 --> 01:36:06,874
- Buon giorno, Miss Sherwood.
- Buon giorno.

1144
01:36:06,957 --> 01:36:11,086
He's in, but I really don't think
he wants to meet anybody.

1145
01:36:28,480 --> 01:36:30,440
Dick?

1146
01:36:33,902 --> 01:36:36,070
Dickie?

1147
01:36:37,614 --> 01:36:39,533
I know you can hear me.

1148
01:36:48,375 --> 01:36:51,669
I was gonna say that I would count to
three, and if you didn't open the door...

1149
01:36:51,753 --> 01:36:56,007
But I won't count anymore.

1150
01:36:56,091 --> 01:36:58,093
On you.

1151
01:37:00,138 --> 01:37:03,640
I won't count on you
anymore.

1152
01:37:07,103 --> 01:37:12,024
Whatever it is you've done
or haven't done,

1153
01:37:12,066 --> 01:37:14,568
you've broken my heart.

1154
01:37:16,821 --> 01:37:19,240
That's one thing
I know you're guilty of.

1155
01:37:26,832 --> 01:37:29,250
And I don't know why.

1156
01:37:31,754 --> 01:37:35,173
I don't know why.
I just don't know why.

1157
01:37:45,017 --> 01:37:47,227
My dear Tom.

1158
01:37:47,310 --> 01:37:50,855
I'm getting out of this.

1159
01:37:50,897 --> 01:37:54,443
Freddie's death. Silvana.

1160
01:37:54,527 --> 01:37:58,740
I've thought about going to the police,
but I can't do it.

1161
01:37:58,781 --> 01:38:01,158
I can't face it.

1162
01:38:01,242 --> 01:38:03,995
I can't face anything anymore.

1163
01:38:04,079 --> 01:38:06,830
I wish I could give you
the life I took for granted.

1164
01:38:09,918 --> 01:38:12,461
You've always understood
what's at the heart of me, Tom.

1165
01:38:12,545 --> 01:38:15,923
Marge never could.

1166
01:38:15,965 --> 01:38:19,385
I suppose that's why
I'm writing this to you,

1167
01:38:19,427 --> 01:38:22,055
the brother I never had.

1168
01:38:22,139 --> 01:38:24,891
The only true friend
I ever had.

1169
01:38:30,564 --> 01:38:32,482
In all kinds of ways,

1170
01:38:32,566 --> 01:38:36,862
you're much more like the son
my father wanted.

1171
01:38:36,945 --> 01:38:40,157
I realize you can
change the people,

1172
01:38:40,240 --> 01:38:42,743
change the scenery,

1173
01:38:42,785 --> 01:38:44,995
but you can't change
your own rotten self.

1174
01:38:47,789 --> 01:38:50,542
Now I can't think what to do
or where to go.

1175
01:38:52,628 --> 01:38:57,215
I'm haunted by everything
I've done and can't undo.

1176
01:38:58,802 --> 01:39:00,761
I'm sorry.

1177
01:39:02,847 --> 01:39:06,225
I've made a mess of being
Dickie Greenleaf, haven't I?

1178
01:40:10,583 --> 01:40:13,587
Tom!

1179
01:40:15,755 --> 01:40:19,050
I'll see you over there!

1180
01:40:27,434 --> 01:40:29,728
I'm so sorry to put you
through this, Peter.

1181
01:40:29,812 --> 01:40:33,398
I just can't face going to the police
by myself when my Italian's so rotten.

1182
01:40:33,481 --> 01:40:35,484
Don't be so daft.
It's fine.

1183
01:40:35,567 --> 01:40:38,195
I'm delighted you finally
made it to Venice.

1184
01:40:38,278 --> 01:40:40,906
I'm delighted, contrary to rumor,
that you're still in one piece.

1185
01:40:40,990 --> 01:40:42,992
- What rumor?
- Oh, you know.

1186
01:40:43,075 --> 01:40:46,495
That Dickie murdered you
and is traveling under your passport.

1187
01:40:46,578 --> 01:40:48,664
I know. It's ridiculous.

1188
01:41:03,513 --> 01:41:05,431
Welcome to Venice.

1189
01:41:05,514 --> 01:41:08,560
God, this place reeks, doesn't it?
Can you smell it?

1190
01:41:08,602 --> 01:41:12,481
Anyway, I've got to
the bottom of the delay, finally.

1191
01:41:12,564 --> 01:41:15,484
We're waiting
for someone from Rome.

1192
01:41:15,567 --> 01:41:17,903
What do you mean?
They've sent for someone from Rome?

1193
01:41:17,945 --> 01:41:21,072
- Well, yes. That's good, isn't it?
- No, I thought...

1194
01:41:21,155 --> 01:41:24,535
that didn't happen in Italy,
that each region is separate.

1195
01:41:24,618 --> 01:41:27,037
I was sure that...
I've read that...

1196
01:41:27,120 --> 01:41:29,956
You've read the papers.
You know what a big deal it's been.

1197
01:41:30,040 --> 01:41:33,085
- American tourist murdered.
- Actually, can we not do this now?

1198
01:41:33,169 --> 01:41:37,255
The stench really is...

1199
01:41:54,525 --> 01:41:59,154
He's taken over the case, 'cause they're
annoyed that the previous chap...

1200
01:41:59,237 --> 01:42:02,115
let Dickie disappear
when he was, um,

1201
01:42:02,156 --> 01:42:04,158
the only suspect
in Freddie's murder.

1202
01:42:07,204 --> 01:42:10,499
In Rome,
about three weeks ago.

1203
01:42:10,541 --> 01:42:12,501
I knew that one.

1204
01:42:19,717 --> 01:42:24,554
Are you a homosexual?
Interesting non sequitur.

1205
01:42:24,638 --> 01:42:26,641
No.

1206
01:42:26,725 --> 01:42:29,977
- No.
- Oh.

1207
01:42:30,018 --> 01:42:34,940
By the way, um, officially
there are no Italian homosexuals.

1208
01:42:35,024 --> 01:42:37,527
Makes Michelangelo and
Leonardo very inconvenient.

1209
01:42:37,611 --> 01:42:39,320
Eh?

1210
01:42:39,362 --> 01:42:42,574
Tell him...
I have a fiancée.

1211
01:42:42,658 --> 01:42:45,035
And Dickie has a fiancée.

1212
01:42:45,075 --> 01:42:48,705
And that Freddie Miles
probably had a string of them.

1213
01:43:00,384 --> 01:43:04,263
Mamma mia.

1214
01:43:07,850 --> 01:43:10,061
- What did he say?
- He says "so many fiancées."

1215
01:43:15,232 --> 01:43:18,235
He's asking... if you
Killed Freddie Miles...

1216
01:43:18,277 --> 01:43:20,238
and then killed Dickie Greenleaf.

1217
01:43:20,279 --> 01:43:24,241
No! No, I did not kill Freddie Miles
and then kill Dickie Greenleaf.

1218
01:43:24,324 --> 01:43:27,537
Is he accusing me?
Ask him if he's accusing me.

1219
01:43:27,578 --> 01:43:30,373
The way it works here,
it's better to be less volatile.

1220
01:43:30,414 --> 01:43:32,584
But it's absurd!

1221
01:43:48,100 --> 01:43:52,563
They found this
in Dickie's place in Rome.

1222
01:43:52,646 --> 01:43:55,232
- You opened this?
- Of course.

1223
01:44:11,540 --> 01:44:14,376
It's a suicide note.

1224
01:44:18,172 --> 01:44:22,051
You asked me all these questions and you
already read this suicide note?

1225
01:44:40,403 --> 01:44:42,489
I don't believe that letter.
Do you?

1226
01:44:42,572 --> 01:44:46,117
Dickie's letter.
Do you believe it?

1227
01:44:46,159 --> 01:44:48,620
I don't know
what to believe.

1228
01:44:48,661 --> 01:44:53,375
Can you imagine, though, if he did
kill Freddie, what that must be like?

1229
01:44:53,500 --> 01:44:57,338
Just to wake up every morning.
I mean, how can you?

1230
01:44:57,420 --> 01:45:00,882
Just wake up and be a person?
Drink your coffee.

1231
01:45:00,966 --> 01:45:05,387
Well, what ever you do,
however terrible, however hurtful,

1232
01:45:05,429 --> 01:45:08,766
it all makes sense,
doesn't it, in your head.

1233
01:45:08,807 --> 01:45:11,601
You never meet anybody
who thinks they're a bad person.

1234
01:45:11,643 --> 01:45:15,689
No, I know, but you're still tormented.
You must be. You've killed someone.

1235
01:45:15,772 --> 01:45:18,901
Don't you just take the past
and put it in a room in the basement,

1236
01:45:18,985 --> 01:45:20,945
and lock the door
and never go in there?

1237
01:45:21,028 --> 01:45:24,407
- That's what I do.
- God, yes.

1238
01:45:24,449 --> 01:45:29,121
But, of course, in my case,
it's probably a whole building.

1239
01:45:29,163 --> 01:45:32,206
And then you meet someone special,

1240
01:45:32,290 --> 01:45:36,335
and all you want to do
is toss them the key.

1241
01:45:37,670 --> 01:45:40,257
Say "Open up. Step inside."

1242
01:45:42,968 --> 01:45:45,179
But you can't...

1243
01:45:45,263 --> 01:45:48,014
because it's dark...

1244
01:45:48,097 --> 01:45:50,976
and there are demons.

1245
01:45:52,019 --> 01:45:54,479
And if anybody saw
how ugly it is...

1246
01:45:59,192 --> 01:46:01,237
Now that's the music talking.

1247
01:46:03,489 --> 01:46:06,826
It's harder to be bleak if you're
playing "Knees Up, Mother Brown."

1248
01:46:12,540 --> 01:46:15,501
I keep wanting to do that.

1249
01:46:15,584 --> 01:46:19,464
Fling...
the door open.

1250
01:46:21,840 --> 01:46:25,595
Just let the light in,
clean everything out.

1251
01:46:27,890 --> 01:46:31,893
If I could take a giant eraser
and rub out everything,

1252
01:46:31,976 --> 01:46:34,896
starting with myself...

1253
01:46:37,482 --> 01:46:40,694
The thing is, Peter, if...

1254
01:46:43,238 --> 01:46:46,867
- Hmm?
- If...

1255
01:46:48,702 --> 01:46:50,663
If...

1256
01:46:57,711 --> 01:47:00,048
No key, huh?

1257
01:47:44,468 --> 01:47:46,469
- Marge.
- Peter.

1258
01:47:48,931 --> 01:47:50,891
- So good to see you.
- Hello, Marge.

1259
01:47:50,932 --> 01:47:53,143
Tom.

1260
01:47:53,226 --> 01:47:57,273
- I see you found Peter.
- I think we sort of found each other.

1261
01:47:57,356 --> 01:48:01,068
- Where's Dickie's father?
- He's not coming till the morning.

1262
01:48:01,152 --> 01:48:04,697
Evidently his stomach. I don't think
the food here is agreeing with him.

1263
01:48:04,780 --> 01:48:06,700
Oh, I was looking forward
to seeing him.

1264
01:48:06,782 --> 01:48:09,493
Dickie hasn't killed himself.
I'm sure of that.

1265
01:48:09,576 --> 01:48:12,121
There's a private detective
on the case now.

1266
01:48:12,205 --> 01:48:14,707
A Mr. MacCarron
Dickie's father's employed.

1267
01:48:14,790 --> 01:48:18,128
- That's a terrific idea.
- He's American.

1268
01:48:18,210 --> 01:48:21,548
He's already discovered
that Dickie cashed checks for $1,000...

1269
01:48:21,631 --> 01:48:23,800
the day before
he disappeared.

1270
01:48:23,883 --> 01:48:25,802
Signora.

1271
01:48:25,886 --> 01:48:29,306
Is that what you do
before you jump into the Tiber?

1272
01:48:29,389 --> 01:48:31,975
I don't think so.

1273
01:48:35,812 --> 01:48:38,023
- Is this you?
- No, it's Tom's.

1274
01:48:38,107 --> 01:48:40,025
Splendid, eh?

1275
01:48:40,108 --> 01:48:43,445
Golly.
Who's paying for this?

1276
01:48:43,487 --> 01:48:45,489
Peter found it for me.

1277
01:48:45,530 --> 01:48:50,452
I can afford it because
it's damp and... falling down.

1278
01:48:50,494 --> 01:48:53,664
- Tom's transformed it.
- This is spectacular.

1279
01:48:53,748 --> 01:48:56,000
That's why
Tom wanted you to stay.

1280
01:48:56,083 --> 01:48:58,670
It's better than trying
to squeeze into my room.

1281
01:48:58,753 --> 01:49:00,838
And I know
How you hate hotels.

1282
01:49:00,922 --> 01:49:02,923
A hotel would have been fine.

1283
01:49:06,385 --> 01:49:10,932
We'll have to tell Mr. Greenleaf
how far his dollar stretched.

1284
01:49:14,311 --> 01:49:17,314
What's funny?

1285
01:49:17,397 --> 01:49:20,942
I was just thinking about when
Tom first came to Mongibello.

1286
01:49:22,986 --> 01:49:26,449
- And look at you now.
- Look at me what?

1287
01:49:27,699 --> 01:49:29,701
To the manor born.

1288
01:49:43,841 --> 01:49:46,051
Mr. Greenleaf?

1289
01:49:49,930 --> 01:49:51,891
Mr. Greenleaf?

1290
01:49:51,933 --> 01:49:55,645
Tom. How are you?
You look well.

1291
01:49:55,728 --> 01:49:58,564
- Thank you, sir. I am well.
- Far cry from New York.

1292
01:49:58,606 --> 01:50:01,108
- Yes, it is.
- Marge.

1293
01:50:01,191 --> 01:50:04,237
Good morning.
Unusual weather.

1294
01:50:04,320 --> 01:50:07,198
- Very.
- And you, sir. Any better?

1295
01:50:07,240 --> 01:50:10,368
Pretty good.
Sticking with hot water.

1296
01:50:10,451 --> 01:50:12,745
- Where's Mr. MacCarron?
- San Remo.

1297
01:50:12,828 --> 01:50:15,582
The police are amateurs.

1298
01:50:15,624 --> 01:50:20,170
Well, my boy, it's come
to a pretty pass, hasn't it?

1299
01:50:20,254 --> 01:50:23,423
What is the detective
hoping to find in San Remo?

1300
01:50:23,507 --> 01:50:28,344
He's being thorough.
I'm learning about my son, Tom.

1301
01:50:28,428 --> 01:50:31,849
Now he's missing,
I'm learning a great deal about him,

1302
01:50:31,932 --> 01:50:35,019
and I hope that you can
fill in some more blanks for me.

1303
01:50:35,102 --> 01:50:38,146
Marge has been good enough
to do that about Mongibello.

1304
01:50:38,230 --> 01:50:42,025
I'll try my best, sir. Obviously,
I'll do anything to help Dickie.

1305
01:50:42,109 --> 01:50:44,569
Good. This theory,

1306
01:50:44,653 --> 01:50:46,781
the letter
he left for you.

1307
01:50:46,864 --> 01:50:50,117
The police think that's
a clear indication...

1308
01:50:50,201 --> 01:50:53,954
he was planning on doing something,
uh, to himself.

1309
01:50:53,996 --> 01:50:56,791
I just don't believe that.

1310
01:50:56,875 --> 01:50:59,419
You don't want to, dear.

1311
01:51:02,630 --> 01:51:04,633
I'd like
to talk to Tom alone.

1312
01:51:04,715 --> 01:51:07,510
Perhaps this afternoon.
Would you mind?

1313
01:51:09,971 --> 01:51:13,975
Marge, what a man may say
to his sweetheart...

1314
01:51:14,059 --> 01:51:16,227
and what he'll admit
to another fellow...

1315
01:51:19,523 --> 01:51:22,234
Such as?

1316
01:51:25,946 --> 01:51:29,200
What a waste of lives and opportunities.

1317
01:51:29,283 --> 01:51:32,285
I'd pay that fellow a hundred dollars
right now to shut up!

1318
01:51:40,628 --> 01:51:44,006
No, Marge doesn't
know the half of it.

1319
01:51:44,047 --> 01:51:47,343
And his passport photo.

1320
01:51:47,385 --> 01:51:50,264
Did you hear? To scratch out
his own face like that?

1321
01:51:50,388 --> 01:51:52,516
Can you imagine?

1322
01:51:52,599 --> 01:51:55,852
Frame of mind
you'd have to be in?

1323
01:51:55,936 --> 01:51:59,230
"I've thought about going to the police,
but I can't face it.

1324
01:51:59,314 --> 01:52:02,859
I can't face
anything anymore."

1325
01:52:02,901 --> 01:52:06,238
I feel guilty. I feel
like I pushed him away.

1326
01:52:06,321 --> 01:52:08,365
I feel like I spoke
and he heard you.

1327
01:52:08,449 --> 01:52:11,243
Well,

1328
01:52:11,326 --> 01:52:13,912
if we all pushed him away,
what about him pushing us away?

1329
01:52:13,995 --> 01:52:16,582
You've been a great friend
to my son.

1330
01:52:16,665 --> 01:52:19,794
Everything is
someone else's fault.

1331
01:52:19,877 --> 01:52:22,337
We all want to sow
wild oats,

1332
01:52:22,421 --> 01:52:25,716
but somebody's got to...
got to...

1333
01:52:25,799 --> 01:52:28,594
What is the word?

1334
01:52:28,678 --> 01:52:31,888
You know, the moment
someone confronts him,

1335
01:52:33,266 --> 01:52:35,768
he lashes out.

1336
01:52:35,852 --> 01:52:38,396
He always has.

1337
01:52:38,479 --> 01:52:42,358
You know, people always say
that you can't choose your parents,

1338
01:52:47,113 --> 01:52:49,575
but you can't choose
your children.

1339
01:52:50,950 --> 01:52:54,537
Dickie.

1340
01:52:54,621 --> 01:52:58,208
You can be a leech.
You can be quite boring.

1341
01:52:58,291 --> 01:53:00,210
- Stop it!
- It's boring.

1342
01:53:04,297 --> 01:53:06,633
Stop, stop, stop!

1343
01:53:08,134 --> 01:53:10,054
- Stop, stop, stop!
- Tommy, Tommy.

1344
01:53:10,138 --> 01:53:12,056
Like a little girl.

1345
01:53:12,139 --> 01:53:15,225
Like a little girl.

1346
01:53:18,854 --> 01:53:20,815
Coming.

1347
01:53:20,899 --> 01:53:23,276
- Sorry. I was asleep.
- Finally.

1348
01:53:23,317 --> 01:53:25,444
- I must have fallen asleep.
- Did Dickie's dad go?

1349
01:53:25,527 --> 01:53:27,488
You look ghastly, Tom.
Did you have a nightmare?

1350
01:53:27,530 --> 01:53:30,741
- He's having an early night.
- Oh, poor man.

1351
01:53:30,824 --> 01:53:33,285
You know, we were banging
on that door forever.

1352
01:53:36,873 --> 01:53:38,833
Uh-oh.

1353
01:53:38,875 --> 01:53:42,462
- I think I've broken a strap.
- Not guilty.

1354
01:53:42,545 --> 01:53:45,506
I'll fix some drinks.

1355
01:53:45,590 --> 01:53:48,218
Ah!
You walk in Venice.

1356
01:53:49,761 --> 01:53:51,679
Are you okay?

1357
01:53:53,182 --> 01:53:55,017
I'm fine.

1358
01:53:55,100 --> 01:53:59,271
- Did you want me to stick around?
- No, it's okay.

1359
01:54:01,314 --> 01:54:03,483
I could come back.

1360
01:54:18,832 --> 01:54:20,960
Your key.

1361
01:54:24,672 --> 01:54:27,342
Tom?

1362
01:54:27,425 --> 01:54:30,929
Marge, I'm in the bath.
I won't be long.

1363
01:54:31,012 --> 01:54:33,222
Tom, I have to speak to you.
It's urgent.

1364
01:54:36,976 --> 01:54:38,895
Coming.

1365
01:54:50,407 --> 01:54:53,702
- I found Dickie's rings.
- What?

1366
01:54:53,785 --> 01:54:55,787
You have Dickie's rings.

1367
01:55:00,584 --> 01:55:02,503
I can explain.

1368
01:55:02,586 --> 01:55:05,255
Dickie promised me he would
Never take off this ring.

1369
01:55:05,339 --> 01:55:08,384
Let me put some clothes on
and we'll talk about this.

1370
01:55:08,468 --> 01:55:10,887
- I have to tell Mr. Greenleaf.
- Marge, you're being hysterical.

1371
01:55:10,970 --> 01:55:14,432
He promised me, "I swear, I will never
take off this ring until we get..."

1372
01:55:14,515 --> 01:55:16,433
Shut up!

1373
01:55:18,645 --> 01:55:22,106
I'm wet, Marge.
I've lost my towel.

1374
01:55:22,190 --> 01:55:25,193
And I'd really like
to put some clothes on.

1375
01:55:25,276 --> 01:55:27,278
Go and pour us both a drink.

1376
01:55:30,699 --> 01:55:32,617
Pour us a drink.

1377
01:56:05,984 --> 01:56:08,320
Marge?

1378
01:56:08,404 --> 01:56:10,656
Where are you going?

1379
01:56:10,739 --> 01:56:14,202
I wasn't snooping.
I just...

1380
01:56:14,285 --> 01:56:17,205
I was looking for a needle
and thread to mend my bra.

1381
01:56:19,207 --> 01:56:22,793
That scent you're wearing.

1382
01:56:22,877 --> 01:56:26,131
I bought that
For you.

1383
01:56:26,172 --> 01:56:28,758
The thing about Dickie...

1384
01:56:28,842 --> 01:56:30,761
So many things.

1385
01:56:32,679 --> 01:56:36,266
That day when he was late
coming back from Rome,

1386
01:56:36,349 --> 01:56:38,267
I tried to tell you this.

1387
01:56:38,351 --> 01:56:41,814
He was with another girl.
I'm not talking about Meredith, either.

1388
01:56:41,897 --> 01:56:45,150
Another girl
that we met in a bar.

1389
01:56:45,192 --> 01:56:48,278
He couldn't be faithful
For five minutes.

1390
01:56:48,362 --> 01:56:50,364
So when he makes a promise,

1391
01:56:50,448 --> 01:56:52,491
it doesn't mean what it means
when you make a promise...

1392
01:56:52,574 --> 01:56:55,161
or I make a promise.

1393
01:56:55,203 --> 01:56:59,206
He has so many realities, Dickie,
and he believes them all.

1394
01:56:59,289 --> 01:57:02,502
He lies. He lies.

1395
01:57:02,543 --> 01:57:06,965
And that's his-Half the time
he doesn't even realize he's doing it.

1396
01:57:07,048 --> 01:57:10,342
And today,

1397
01:57:10,384 --> 01:57:14,180
I really started wondering whether
he may have killed Freddie.

1398
01:57:14,264 --> 01:57:17,851
He would get so crazy
If anybody would contradict him.

1399
01:57:17,934 --> 01:57:20,645
Well, you know that.
You know that.

1400
01:57:20,728 --> 01:57:23,357
You know that.

1401
01:57:23,399 --> 01:57:25,692
And that's the irony, Marge.

1402
01:57:25,733 --> 01:57:27,695
I loved you.

1403
01:57:27,736 --> 01:57:29,696
You may as well know, Marge.
I loved you.

1404
01:57:29,738 --> 01:57:32,491
I don't know, maybe it's
grotesque of me to say this now,

1405
01:57:32,573 --> 01:57:35,368
so just... write it on apiece
of paper or something...

1406
01:57:35,452 --> 01:57:37,912
and put it in your purse
for a rainy day.

1407
01:57:37,997 --> 01:57:42,208
"Tom loves me. Tom loves me."

1408
01:57:42,292 --> 01:57:44,670
- Why do you have Dickie's rings?
- I told you.

1409
01:57:44,753 --> 01:57:47,840
- He gave them to me.
- Why? When?

1410
01:57:47,923 --> 01:57:50,926
I feel as if you haven't been listening
to anything I've been saying to you.

1411
01:57:51,009 --> 01:57:54,263
I don't believe you.
I don't believe you.

1412
01:57:54,347 --> 01:57:56,682
- It's all true.
- I don't believe...

1413
01:57:56,766 --> 01:58:01,145
a single word you've said.

1414
01:58:01,229 --> 01:58:03,940
You're shivering, Marge.
Look at you.

1415
01:58:04,023 --> 01:58:07,819
Marge, can I hold you?

1416
01:58:07,902 --> 01:58:09,862
Will you let me hold you?

1417
01:58:09,945 --> 01:58:11,990
Marge?

1418
01:58:12,115 --> 01:58:15,159
- Peter! Thank God you're here.
- What's going on?

1419
01:58:15,243 --> 01:58:18,579
Get me out of here.
Get me out of here. Please!

1420
01:58:18,663 --> 01:58:23,501
Tom, are you okay?

1421
01:58:23,543 --> 01:58:26,672
You try.
You try talking to her.

1422
01:58:27,756 --> 01:58:29,841
- Tom?
- I give up.

1423
01:58:29,924 --> 01:58:32,511
Tell me what's going on.
Tom!

1424
01:58:32,594 --> 01:58:35,055
- What did I ever do to her?
- Listen...

1425
01:58:35,138 --> 01:58:38,267
Have her tell you one thing
that I've ever done to her.

1426
01:58:38,351 --> 01:58:41,019
You can't be angry
with her.

1427
01:58:41,102 --> 01:58:44,064
She's confused, and she needs
someone to blame.

1428
01:58:44,106 --> 01:58:46,066
So she blames you.

1429
01:58:46,108 --> 01:58:48,694
I'll go back home
and talk to her.

1430
01:58:48,736 --> 01:58:51,238
As for you,

1431
01:58:51,322 --> 01:58:53,950
either get a safety razor
or grow a beard.

1432
01:59:06,963 --> 01:59:10,133
- Is Mr. Greenleaf here?
- Mr. Ripley?

1433
01:59:10,217 --> 01:59:12,886
- Yes.
- I'm Alvin MacCarron.

1434
01:59:15,597 --> 01:59:18,266
I don't know,
I don't know. I just know it.

1435
01:59:18,349 --> 01:59:21,270
Marge, there's female
intuition and then there are facts.

1436
01:59:23,855 --> 01:59:25,775
- Tom.
- Sir.

1437
01:59:25,858 --> 01:59:28,569
Marge, you should have waited.
I didn't...

1438
01:59:28,652 --> 01:59:31,321
Didn't Peter say I'd
come by and pick you up?

1439
01:59:32,448 --> 01:59:35,075
Marge has been telling us
about the rings.

1440
01:59:35,117 --> 01:59:37,620
Yes, I feel ridiculous
I didn't mention them yesterday.

